    <text>
        <body>
             <div type="edition" subtype="ogham" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="pgl-Ogam" resp="#POC"><!--update lang and resp here-->              
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:up"/><g ref="#forfid_X"/>ᚅ<g ref="#bound_D"/>ᚇ<g ref="#hammerhead_A"/>ᚉᚈᚐ<unclear reason="worn">ᚅ</unclear>ᚔᚋᚂᚁ
                </ab> 
            </div>
            <div type="edition" subtype="transliteration" xml:lang="pgl-Ogam" xml:space="preserve" resp="#POC">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:up"/><g ref="#forfid_X" type="interpretation_E"/>N<g ref="#bound_D"/>D<g ref="#hammerhead_A"/>CTA<unclear reason="worn">N</unclear>IMLB
                </ab>
                <ab type="list">XNDDACTANIMLB</ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                <app n="1"> 
                    <note>Though the letters are relatively clear, it is difficult to know where to start. Forsyth (1995, 684) takes the X forfid as the first letter and reads anti-clockwise:</note>
                    <rdg source="FOR1995b">ENDDACTANIM(v/lb) or possibly bENDDACTANIMl.</rdg>
 <note>Proposed (Gaelic) readings include: VENDDACTANIM; or T’ANIM VENDDAC (Rodway 2017); or BENDDACTANIML (Forsyth 1995).</note>   
                </app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation">
                <p>Possible translations of the text include VENDDACTANIM; or T’ANIM VENDDAC, meaning ‘(from) your dear Findach’ (Rodway 2017); or if the text is read as BENDDACTANIML or BENDDACT ANIM L‘a blessing on the soul of L’ (Forsyth 1996, 176)</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                 <p>Forsyth (1995, 688) confirms that there is slight doubt over the twelfth letter which is probably LB but could possibly be interpreted as F or V, but the rest ENDDACTANIM- is secure. Interpreting the text as BENDDACT ANIM L, BENDDACT is Old Irish <foreign xml:lang="sga"><ref target="https://dil.ie/5661">bendacht</ref></foreign>, 'a blessing', from Latin <foreign xml:lang="la">benedictum</foreign>, and ANIM, Old Irish <foreign xml:lang="sga"><ref target="https://dil.ie/1402">anim</ref></foreign> 'soul'. This word is not to be confused with Old Irish <foreign xml:lang="sga">ainm</foreign> 'name', which occurs in its older form ANM on a number of ogham pillars in Southern Ireland.</p>
                <p>The formula <foreign xml:lang="sga">bendacht for anim N.</foreign>, 'a blessing on the soul of N.', is well attested in the Irish epigraphic record, mainly on recumbent cross-slabs. </p>
            </div>
